Lyme Regis, Dorset, England":"Lyme Regis, Dorset, England","Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England":"Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England","Sissinghurst, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Sissinghurst, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"en":{"Abt 1446–1525":"about 1446–1525","1446–1525":"1446–1525","1450–1535":"1450–1535","1472–1565":"1472–1565","1442–1475":"1442–1475","1446–1480":"1446–1480","Abt 1472":"about 1472","1525":"1525","1535":"1535","1446":"1446","1466":"1466","1565":"1565","1475":"1475","1442":"1442","Abt 1446":"about 1446","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","Lyme Regis, Dorset, England":"Lyme Regis, Dorset, England","Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England":"Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England","Sissinghurst, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Sissinghurst, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Baker","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name, from Middle English <i>bakere</i>, Old English <i>bæcere</i>, a derivative of <i>bacan</i> ‘to bake’. It may have been used for someone whose special task in the kitchen of a great house or castle was the baking of bread, but since most humbler households did their own baking in the Middle Ages, it may also have referred to the owner of a communal oven used by the whole village. The right to be in charge of this and exact money or loaves in return for its use was in many parts of the country a hereditary feudal privilege. Compare   Miller  . Less often the surname may have been acquired by someone noted for baking particularly fine bread or by a baker of pottery or bricks.","Americanized form (translation into English) of surnames meaning ‘baker’, for example Dutch   Bakker  , German   Becker   and   Beck  , French   Boulanger   and <b>Bélanger</b> (see   Belanger  ), Czech <b>Pekař</b>, Slovak <b>Pekár</b>, and Croatian   Pekar  .","History: Baker was established as an early immigrant surname in Puritan New England. Among others, two men called Remember Baker (father and son) lived at Woodbury, CT, in the early 17th century, and an Alexander Baker arrived in Boston, MA, in 1635."],"variants":[{"name":"Miller","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for a miller. The standard modern vocabulary word represents the northern Middle English term <i>miller</i>, an agent derivative of <i>mille</i> ‘mill’, reinforced by Old Norse <i>mylnari</i> (see   Milner  ). In southern, western, and central England   Millward   (literally, ‘mill keeper’) was the usual term. In North America, the surname <i>Miller</i> has absorbed many cognate surnames from other languages, for example German <b>Müller</b> (see   Mueller  ), Dutch   Mulder   and   Molenaar  , French   Meunier  , Italian   Molinaro  , Spanish   Molinero  , Hungarian <b>Molnár</b> (see   Molnar  ), Slovenian, Croatian, and Serbian   Mlinar  , Polish <b>Młynarz</b> or <b>Młynarczyk</b> (see   Mlynarczyk  ). <i>Miller</i> (including in the senses below) is the seventh most frequent surname in the US.","South German, Swiss German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of <b>Müller</b> ‘miller’ (see   Mueller  ) and, in North America, also an altered form of this. This form of the surname is also found in other European countries, notably in Poland, Denmark, France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), and Czechia; compare 3 below.","Americanized form of Polish, Czech, Croatian, Serbian, and Slovenian   Miler   ‘miller’, a surname of German origin."]},{"name":"Baxter","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>baxter</i> ‘baker’ (from Old English <i>bæcestre</i> ‘baker’, earlier ‘female baker’, the feminine equivalent of <i>bæcere</i>). Compare   Baker  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Thomas Baker was born about 1446, his father, Simon Baker, was 5 and his mother, Lady Mary Broom, was 1. He had at least 1 daughter with Lady Joan Barrett. He died in 1525, in Sissinghurst, Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 80."},"et":{"Abt 1446–1525":"umbes 1446–1525","1446–1525":"1446–1525","1450–1535":"1450–1535","1472–1565":"1472–1565","1442–1475":"1442–1475","1446–1480":"1446–1480","Abt 1472":"umbes 1472","1525":"1525","1535":"1535","1446":"1446","1466":"1466","1565":"1565","1475":"1475","1442":"1442","Abt 1446":"umbes 1446","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","Lyme Regis, Dorset, England":"Lyme Regis, Dorset, England","Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England":"Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England","Sissinghurst, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Sissinghurst, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1446–1525":"noin 1446–1525","1446–1525":"1446–1525","1450–1535":"1450–1535","1472–1565":"1472–1565","1442–1475":"1442–1475","1446–1480":"1446–1480","Abt 1472":"noin 1472","1525":"1525","1535":"1535","1446":"1446","1466":"1466","1565":"1565","1475":"1475","1442":"1442","Abt 1446":"noin 1446","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","Lyme Regis, Dorset, England":"Lyme Regis, Dorset, England","Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England":"Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England","Sissinghurst, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Sissinghurst, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1446–1525":"environ 1446–1525","1446–1525":"1446–1525","1450–1535":"1450–1535","1472–1565":"1472–1565","1442–1475":"1442–1475","1446–1480":"1446–1480","Abt 1472":"environ 1472","1525":"1525